cs.MA, cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SY, cs.AI

Reasoning: 
1. cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems) - The title of the paper mentions "Multi Agent Scenarios" and the abstract talks about a distributed algorithm where processing units are communicating with each other to reach a global goal. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Multi-Agent Systems sub-category.
2. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with detecting impaired and noisy nodes over a network, which involves information transmission and processing. This makes the Information Theory sub-category a likely fit.
3. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper deals with network interference cancellation, which is a key aspect of networking and internet architecture. This sub-category is therefore a possible fit.
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The paper proposes an algorithm to adapt sharing weights according to the behavior of agents, which involves control and optimization. This makes the Systems and Control sub-category a possible fit.
5. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) - The paper applies the introduced algorithm to a multi-agent RL scenario, which involves artificial intelligence and machine learning. This makes the Artificial Intelligence sub-category a possible fit.
